{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ff58bdab-bde5-43bc-b5c0-75bc5e4beaa2","content":"The repo is empty, so I'll create the GitHub Actions workflow and walk you through the NuGet.org configuration.","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_01NXLc7tN1uKcHkhaU5P9T5k","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p /tmp/sv-0d0cedee072347bb8b00182412f1a511/.github/workflows","description":"Create workflows directory"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Create workflows directory"}],"interactionId":"880af0a4-2610-4415-a9df-9edd03f204f8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty. I need to help them set up:\n\n1. The GitHub Actions workflow for publishing with OIDC trusted publishing\n2. Guide them on NuGet.org configuration\n\nLet me create the workflow file. NuGet trusted publishing uses OIDC tokens from GitHub Actions to authenticate with NuGet.org without API keys. The key pieces are:\n\n1. The workflow needs `id-token: write` permission\n2. Use `dotnet nuget push` with `--source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json` and the OIDC token\n\n\n3. On NuGet.org, I'll need to configure the trusted publisher by specifying the GitHub repository, workflow file, and optionally the environment so the OIDC token exchange works properly.\n\n4. In the GitHub Actions workflow, I need to request the OIDC token and use it to authenticate—either by passing it directly as an API key or exchanging it through NuGet.org's endpoint for a short-lived key.\n\n5. The workflow setup requires `id-token: write` permissions and uses the `dotnet` CLI to handle the authentication and push.\n\nWriting the workflow example... I'm realizing the `dotnet` CLI doesn't have native OIDC support, so the workflow needs to explicitly request an OIDC token from GitHub, exchange it with NuGet.org for a temporary API key, and then pass that key to the push command. There might be an official action that handles this flow, but I should verify the exact mechanism before recommending it.\n\nBuilding out a GitHub Actions workflow that handles the packing and publishing steps...\n\nThe publish job runs in a protected environment with OIDC token permissions, downloads the built artifacts, and pushes them to NuGet using the trusted publisher flow — though I'm uncertain whether `dotnet nuget push` automatically leverages the OIDC token in this setup.","outputTokens":1559},"id":"d32868e8-3a53-4d75-a676-57a509178e12","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:42:22.853Z","parentId":"5182393a-edcf-4189-8c3f-2c269521d495"}
