{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"06380a77-3742-460d-ba02-c45b8f77559f","content":"Workflow created at `.github/workflows/publish.yml`. Here's what it does and what you still need to configure:\n\n---\n\n### Workflow overview\n\n| Job | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| **pack** | Checks out code, runs `dotnet pack`, uploads the `.nupkg` as an artifact |\n| **publish** | Downloads the artifact and pushes to nuget.org using OIDC — **no API key stored anywhere** |\n\nThe jobs are split so the publish job runs with minimal permissions (`id-token: write` only) in a protected environment.\n\n---\n\n### Steps to complete on nuget.org\n\n1. **Go to** nuget.org → your account → **Manage Packages** → select your package (or set this up on first publish via **Upload Package → Trusted Publishers**).\n2. **Add a Trusted Publisher** with:\n   - **Repository owner:** `myorg`\n   - **Repository name:** `mylib`\n   - **Workflow:** `publish.yml`\n   - **Environment:** `nuget-publish`\n3. Save.\n\n### Steps to complete on GitHub\n\n1. In your repo **Settings → Environments**, create an environment called **`nuget-publish`**. Optionally add required reviewers for gated releases.\n\n### Publishing a release\n\n```bash\ngit tag v1.0.0\ngit push origin v1.0.0\n```\n\nThe tag push triggers the workflow. The OIDC token exchange happens automatically — no secrets to rotate.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"880af0a4-2610-4415-a9df-9edd03f204f8","outputTokens":346},"id":"aba89672-96c4-47fd-b72f-a8fbf74a41d1","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:42:42.092Z","parentId":"8db05108-8742-47f1-b22c-5685a409cfdd"}
